=========================================
LINUX SECURITY CHEAT SHEET
(AppArmor • SELinux • TCP Wrappers • iptables)
=========================================

-------------------------------------------------
1. SECURITY MODELS
-------------------------------------------------

DAC  = Discretionary Access Control
MAC  = Mandatory Access Control
RBAC = Role-Based Access Control

Linux Permissions → DAC
SELinux/AppArmor → MAC

-------------------------------------------------
2. SELINUX
-------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
Mandatory Access Control (MAC)
Uses labels (contexts) to determine access.

Status

getenforce
sestatus

Modes

Enforcing
Permissive
Disabled

Temporarily change mode

sudo setenforce 0     # Permissive
sudo setenforce 1     # Enforcing

View file contexts

ls -Z

View process contexts

ps -eZ

Restore default context

restorecon -Rv /path

-------------------------------------------------
3. APPARMOR
-------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
Mandatory Access Control (MAC)
Restricts applications using path-based profiles.

Status

aa-status

Loaded profiles

apparmor_status

Enable profile

aa-enforce /etc/apparmor.d/profile

Complain mode (log only)

aa-complain /etc/apparmor.d/profile

Disable profile

aa-disable /etc/apparmor.d/profile

-------------------------------------------------
4. TCP WRAPPERS
-------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
Host-based access control for TCP services.
Uses:
/etc/hosts.allow
/etc/hosts.deny

Order:
1. Check hosts.allow
2. Check hosts.deny
3. Default policy

Allow SSH from one IP

sshd: 192.168.1.100

Allow entire subnet

sshd: 192.168.1.

Allow everyone

ALL: ALL

Deny everyone

ALL: ALL

Example

/etc/hosts.allow
----------------
sshd: 192.168.1.50

/etc/hosts.deny
---------------
ALL: ALL

NOTE:
TCP Wrappers are deprecated and many modern Linux
distributions/services no longer support them.

-------------------------------------------------
5. IPTABLES
-------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
Linux kernel firewall.

Common Chains

INPUT
OUTPUT
FORWARD

Default Policies

ACCEPT
DROP
REJECT

-------------------------------------------------
6. VIEW RULES
-------------------------------------------------

iptables -L
iptables -L -n
iptables -L -v
iptables -S

-------------------------------------------------
7. DEFAULT POLICY
-------------------------------------------------

Accept everything

iptables -P INPUT ACCEPT

Drop everything

iptables -P INPUT DROP

-------------------------------------------------
8. ALLOW / BLOCK TRAFFIC
-------------------------------------------------

Allow SSH

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

Allow HTTP

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT

Allow HTTPS

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT

Allow ICMP (Ping)

iptables -A INPUT -p icmp -j ACCEPT

Drop Telnet

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 23 -j DROP

Reject FTP

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 21 -j REJECT

-------------------------------------------------
9. ALLOW ESTABLISHED CONNECTIONS
-------------------------------------------------

iptables -A INPUT \
-m conntrack \
--ctstate ESTABLISHED,RELATED \
-j ACCEPT

-------------------------------------------------
10. ALLOW LOOPBACK
-------------------------------------------------

iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT

-------------------------------------------------
11. ALLOW SPECIFIC IP
-------------------------------------------------

iptables -A INPUT \
-s 192.168.1.100 \
-j ACCEPT

-------------------------------------------------
12. BLOCK SPECIFIC IP
-------------------------------------------------

iptables -A INPUT \
-s 192.168.1.100 \
-j DROP

-------------------------------------------------
13. DELETE RULES
-------------------------------------------------

List with numbers

iptables -L --line-numbers

Delete by number

iptables -D INPUT 3

Flush all rules

iptables -F

Delete all chains

iptables -X

-------------------------------------------------
14. SAVE RULES
-------------------------------------------------

Debian/Ubuntu

iptables-save

Restore

iptables-restore

-------------------------------------------------
15. COMMON MATCHES
-------------------------------------------------

Protocol

-p tcp
-p udp
-p icmp

Source IP

-s IP

Destination IP

-d IP

Input Interface

-i eth0

Output Interface

-o eth0

Destination Port

--dport 80

Source Port

--sport 53

Connection State

-m conntrack --ctstate NEW
-m conntrack --ctstate ESTABLISHED
-m conntrack --ctstate RELATED

-------------------------------------------------
16. QUICK FIREWALL
-------------------------------------------------

Allow loopback

iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT

Allow established

iptables -A INPUT -m conntrack \
--ctstate ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

Allow SSH

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp \
--dport 22 -j ACCEPT

Allow HTTP

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp \
--dport 80 -j ACCEPT

Allow HTTPS

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp \
--dport 443 -j ACCEPT

Drop everything else

iptables -P INPUT DROP

